observations.recommendation:
We commended the LCE for managing to implement the PPAs included in the AIP and pursuant to DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-01.  However, we recommended that the LCE

(a)  require the GSO Chief and Municipal Engineer (ME) to hire laborers/workers who are residents of the Municipality for projects implemented by Administration;

(b)  undertake procurement of infrastructure projects through competitive public bidding and resort to the alternative methods of procurement only in highly exceptional cases;

(c) require the BAC members to submit the technical eligibility documents and other contract supporting documents; and

(d) require the MA to check the completeness of supporting documents before payments are made.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to

(a) prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring job orders;

(b) hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months;

(c) avoid the hiring of job orders whose functions overlap/duplicate those of the regular employees of the Municipality especially the accountable officers; and

(d)  submit to the audit team the Contract of Service and copy of government issued valid IDs to evaluate the necessity and validity of all JO personnel employed as of December 31, 2019.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Head of the General Services Office to

cause the preparation of the updated Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property together with the corresponding assessment, evaluation and appraisal reports; 

(b) facilitate the submission of request for disposal of said PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for inspection, evaluation and review by the COA Technical Services Office; 

(c) ensure that after receipt of favorable COA recommendation on the request,  undertake immediate disposal of the subject properties to prevent further deterioration, decline of value and in order to generate additional funds from sale thereof; and 

(d) prepare and submit the regular schedule of disposal of assets once the same became unserviceable and beyond economical repairs to avoid the accumulation of unserviceable PPEs in the storage facility and to prevent the recurrence of similar lapses.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive

(a) continue to monitor the review and approval timeline of the LSWMP for its prompt implementation and realization;

(b) continue the planned improvements for the MRF as well as the trainings lined up for the MRF personnel;

(c) intensify its information campaign on proper waste segregation and waste minimization by organizing barangay level hands-on trainings/seminars where the public have first-hand experience on how to properly segregate household garbage and on how to apply waste minimization measures like composting, recycling, etc. in their own backyard; and

(d) designate marshals who shall monitor the compliance of the public to local ordinances on solid waste management. Further, the Municipality should strictly adhere to the provision of RA 9184 relative to Alternative Mode of Procurement.

We recommended that Management 

(a) require the Municipal Accountant to record in the books the cost of the completed Multi-Purpose Building although there was no final payment yet and acceptance of the project was not effected by the Management. The fact that the LGU uses the building is tantamount to its acceptance; 

(b) create a special committee to account for its real properties specially the lots covered only by tax declarations for titling and proper recording in the books; 

(c) in reiteration to previous year’s recommendation, create a special committee that shall undertake inventory of all fixed and non-fixed assets of the  Municipality including those funded by SEF to facilitate the preparation/update of required PPE records and reports; and 

(d) require the GSO and MAO to organize property cards and equipment/real property cards as a medium in the reconciliation of records.

We recommended that Management 

(a) continue to monitor the review and approval timeline of the LSWMP for its prompt implementation and realization; 

(b) continue the planned improvements for the MRF as well as the trainings lined up for the MRF personnel; 

(c) intensify its information campaign on proper waste segregation and waste minimization by organizing barangay level hands-on trainings/seminars where the public have first-hand experience on how to properly segregate household garbage and on how to apply waste minimization measures like composting, recycling, etc. in their own backyard; and 

(d) designate marshals who shall monitor the compliance of the public to local ordinances on solid waste management.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to 

(a) prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring job orders;

(b) hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months; 

(c) avoid the hiring of job orders whose functions overlap/duplicate those of the regular employees of the Municipality especially the accountable officers; and 

(d)  submit to the audit team the Contract of Service and copy of government issued valid IDs to evaluate the necessity and validity of all JO personnel employed as of December 31, 2018.

We recommended that Management instruct the LDRRMC to 

(a) strengthen the planning and budget linkage so as to help the Municipality in attaining its vision, goals, and objectives; 

(b) monitor and review the progress and challenges in the implementation of the disaster risk reduction and management plan and to develop an elaborated action plan to ensure the fulfillment of programmed PPAs; 

(c) formulate  programs, projects and activities for the full amount of unexpended LDRRMF pursuant to  COA Circular 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;  and, 

(d) comply with the disaster preparedness minimum standards to mitigate the effects of disaster, and strengthen the capacities to anticipate, cope and recover from negative impacts of any catastrophe.

We recommended that Management 

(a) continue its efforts to improve its GAD planning and budgeting; 

(b) to continue organizing various workshops to strengthen its GFPS and spread GAD awareness among its employees; and 

(c) ensure that the provisions of the GAD Code are implemented.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management 

(a) plan the establishment of a centralized GAD database to help in identifying emerging gender issues; 

(b) ensure that the required documents in the GAD AR are complete and supportive of what is reported in the AR; 

(c) study/consider the possible establishment of a GAD office that will support and coordinate the initiatives of the GFPS and for proper monitoring and evaluation of all GAD related PPA's.

We recommended that the:

a. Local Chief Executive

(i) prioritize the placement of the three mandatory staff personnel at the MDRRMO to handle the administration and training, research and planning, and operations and warning to effectively and efficiently address the requirements of the above-cited existing rules and regulations on disaster preparedness, mitigation, recovery and response; and 

(ii) as head of the MDC, fast track the preparation and approval of the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP) and Comprehensive Land-Use Plan (CLUP) in order that disaster risk management could be integrated to the development plan; 

b. Members of the MDRRMC ensure that the members-CSOs/NGOs to the Council possess the eligibility requirements cited under NDRRMC No.  3 to assure of effective and strengthened citizen’s participation in the locality;

c. Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer install an effective internal control in the recording, maintenance and distribution of relief items and disaster response equipment in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Management 

(a) initiate capacity building programs on GAD especially for the members of the GFPS to strengthen their knowledge and be able to perform their duties productively; 

(b) plan the establishment of a centralized GAD database to help in identifying emerging gender issues; 

(c) create a separate GAD office that will support and coordinate the initiatives of the GFPS and for proper monitoring and evaluation of all GAD related PPA's; and 

(d) ask the Sanggunian to formulate and pass a GAD Code or ordinance.

We recommended that Management require the Accounting Office to: 

(a) ensure that the remittances of premiums and loan amortizations are intact; 

(b) make representations with the GSIS, Philhealth, and Pag-IBIG for reconciliation of records to address promptly the under(over) remittances of premiums and loans.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the concerned Municipal officials to 

(a) reconstitute the SWMB to include the required members/representatives as prescribed in R.A. No. 9003; 

(b) expedite the necessary revisions and disposal of comments in the ESWMP for the review and approval of the Sangguniang Bayan and of the NSWMC; 

(c) strictly follow the rules and regulations set forth R.A. No. 9003, and monitor the implementation of various Ordinances made by the Sangguniang Pambayan in connection with solid waste management for strict enforcement; 

(d) invest more on facilities such as equipment in order to promote agriculture, and composting to decrease the cost of hauling, and lessen the residual wastes transferred to the sanitary landfill; 

(e) provide the segregators and collectors with personal protective gears to protect them from the waste hazards; and 

(f) induce the cooperation of business owners as well as the public commuters in maintaining the cleanliness of the surroundings.

We recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive (i) prioritize the placement of the three mandatory staff personnel at the MDRRMO to handle the administration and training, research and planning, and operations and warning to effectively and efficiently address the requirements of the above-cited existing rules and regulations on disaster preparedness, mitigation, recovery and response; and (ii) as head of the MDC, fast track the preparation and approval of the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP) and Comprehensive Land-Use Plan (CLUP) in order that disaster risk management could be integrated to the development plan;
Members of the MDRRMC ensure that the members-CSOs/NGOs to the Council possess the eligibility requirements cited under NDRRMC No.  3 to assure of effective and strengthened citizen’s participation in the locality;
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer install an effective internal control in the recording, maintenance and distribution of relief items and disaster response equipment in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Government; 

(a) release immediately the RPT shares due to the said barangays, otherwise, the filing of appropriate administrative and/or criminal action be instituted against the personnel responsible in the holding back of such shares and;


(b) strictly comply with Section 271(d) of RA 7160 in releasing the RPT shares of the barangays.

We recommended that Management 

(a) instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat to strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184, specifically on the consolidation of all adjusted PPMPs into one single APP that is consistent with its duly approved budget; 

(b) strictly comply with the provisions of Section 7.2 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 that no procurement shall be authorized and undertaken unless these are included in the APP.

We recommended that management  

(a) coordinate with the Local School Board to stop the procurement of Instructional Materials until the lifting of the Moratorium; 

(b) henceforth comply strictly  with DEPED Order No. 44 dated September 26, 2013 to avoid suspension of transactions.
